How come the colonial money that is spent in Lesotho just doesn\rquote t seem to do anything? Doesn\rquote t seem to make any difference?\'94 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid2902961 She felt c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 ulture shock, and realizing that in the Basuto circle, \'93it\rquote 
s more of an honour to be visited than to be invited, so if you want to spend time with an African family you invite yourself\'94.  She also experienced anxiety about maintaining certain standards that were expected of a white woman \endash 
 such as not having to carry her own water and sweep her own house.   
\par 
\par The experience of trauma \endash  in her case being ill and becoming vulnerabl
e to the point of being cared for by a local woman.  This experience removed the stereotype of the strong white person, and as being strong, and removed the social boundary to the point where the locals no longer called her \'93Madam\'94
 and instead began to call her \'93Osi\'94 meaning \'93Big Sister\'94.  
\par 
\par She learned kinship analysis \'93on the ground\'94 from the curious children who came looking into her hut, giggling, pointing and nudging each other.  From these children she learnt that kinship meant different things for different people.  
\par 
\par Being in \'93the field\'94 made her realize that the things she had been taught are kind of packages that had to be turned into a framework, a holistic package, in order to interpret people\rquote s lives in the round.  
\par 
\par After her PhD research she moved to Toronto, Canada to teach at University of Toronto.  While teaching in Toronto she did some urban study on a project that was run by someone else.  
\par 
\par The family moved to Toronto because her husband wanted to do a PhD at University of Toronto.  She worked in the Anthropology Department, and the family remained in Toronto for nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid161623 
 years where three of their four }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 children were born.     
\par 
\par After Toronto the family returned to England and she worked for the Ethnic Relations Unit at University of Bristol with Michael Banton.  
\par 
\par In London she conducted the first studies on the Battersea project, questioning the notion that ethnicity always counts \endash  which she doesn\rquote t believe.  The Battersea project revealed that ethnicity didn\rquote 
t always count, and she did a comparison study with Bow where she found that ethnicity did count.  
\par 
\par The Battersea/Bow comparative study allowed her to build a model of local systems being more closed/more open, and the implications of that
 for whether ethnicity counts, and whether people are rejected or included.  She is currently finishing the book on this comparative work called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 
The Capability of Places: A Classification of Local Systems}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 . This work looks at a whole system, questioning how you define a whole system and what i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5533721 s the character of that system.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 
\par 
\par From her work in London she realized that within the same city with adjacent neighbourhoods can exist completely different sort of dynamics which affect the way ethnicity is treated, and which also affects economics and migration.  
\par 
\par She disagrees with the tendency from the outside to assign people one identity.  She believes instead that we are all living with lots of identities.  Through all her work there is a common thread regarding h
er interest in looking at how people manage their lives and how the local environment lets then do so or doesn\rquote t let them do so, what resources they have and the kind of mix of identity and economics involved.  
\par 
\par While in London she took a year off and wen
t to teach in Stockholm where she made some contacts, in particular with a Medical Research Institute which was working in Africa - Zambia.  After that she did her study with the Kampala women looking at HIV and other sexually transmitted diseases.  The o
bjective was to understand why people don\rquote t get these diseases treated?  She was aware of the issues in people\rquote s lives with regards to money, shame etc., but she needed to have \'93a question which made sense in the real world\'94.  
\par 
\par Her Battersea study was conducted by a team of multi-disciplinary researchers \endash  an interdisciplinary approach to doing research which was very innovative at the time (in the early 1980\rquote 
s).   According to her, such applied, multi-disciplinary, urban, at home society study were not pop
ular among anthropologists at the time.  Ironically, on the basis of this type of work, she was later asked to be the Chair of the Association of Social Anthropologists (ASA). 
\par 
\par She believes that if your objective is to solve, or illuminate at least a practical problem, then you pull in whatever tools you can find, whereas if your objective is to do somet}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5533721 hing \'93
beautiful and anthropological}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 \'94 then you don\rquote t.  The latter never interested her.
\par 
\par She makes a distinction between \'93method\'94 and \'93methodology\'94.  To her methods \'93are strategies for finding out what you want to find out, whereas the methodology is the \'93ology\'94 \endash  What\rquote 
s the argument here?  What is the justification for putting all this stuff together?\'94  In her current book, the methods chapter is called, \'93Three Sets of Methods and One Methodology\'94.  The question (\'93
How can I find out what kind of a local system this is?\'94), argument and framework are the same in each of the three studies.  However, because the contexts are different, the researchers have had to
 adjust to the setting, the resources they have, the problem and so forth (these are different).  
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid4722222 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 
