re not saying, \lquote Okay, what does the sociologist have to say about this?\rquote   You\rquote re saying, \lquote What do we know about the milk jug?\rquote   And so the \lquote ology\rquote  is built round the milk jug, round the question\'85 what i
s the question?  And how would you, from your perspective, approach that question?  And how can we do it together?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5533721  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 
... The \lquote ology\rquote  has to be shared\'94.
\par 
\par In terms of methods, she has always used local people as interviewers, which can have pros and cons.  However, with regard to cons, she believes that\rquote s not a bad thing, because it made them ask the question, \'93Why?\'94
  And it turned out that for the Battersea study, for example, the interviewers were really not part of the local fabric, in that they were never t
here, they had funny timetables.  They did not only use local people, but they allow the interviewers to select who th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9637019 ey interviewed. However,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222  \'93the business of who is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 
 the community, and who is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 out}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 , and why, comes actually from letting local people decid
e who they want in\'94.
\par 
\par In using locals as interviewers she designed the interview guide in a manner which avoided intrusive and personal questions. Consequently, the information on the ethnographic survey was information that everybody knew such as, \'93What A
ssociations do you belong to?\'94 \'93Who cooks the main meal?\'94 
\par 
\par In the second phase - which was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 Eight London Household}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 
 phase - where the interviewing was done by a member of her research team, they found that they still needed to be careful about the kind of arrangement where people could say, \'93No, I\rquote m not going to talk about that\'94
, or where they could say things which they afterwards didn\rquote t want printed.  
\par 
\par She believes that the strangeness of the researcher }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9637019 is sometimes a great thing, but}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 
 the method of combining the insiders and the outsiders can reveal some thorough information, \'93thick description\'94 (Geertz). 
\par 
\par She spoke of the difference between doing research in an \'93exotic\'94
 culture where the effort is to normalize it and working in a familiar culture where the effort is to problematize it.   She thinks that it is better not to include personal questions in a questionnai
re, but rather to have conversations in order to gain answers to personal questions.  
