\par 
\par The outcome for the Kampala project was the recognition that the trad
itional healers were doing a good job.  She highlights, through her illustration, the need for combining local/insider knowledge with scientific knowledge in the treatment of sexually transmitted diseases. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid14693483 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4722222\charrsid4722222 Raymond Firth\rquote s style of teaching was something 
she tried to emulate.  He was the kind of teacher who, when a student got something wrong, he would pick up on what they said and make something interesting and positive out of it.
\par 
\par She loved Audrey Richards\rquote  humour; Robert Payne for her is one of the most original current thinkers who is refreshing and clever, and who approaches an issue from sideways; Ernest Gellner was good on the \'93ologies\'94
, the framing of problems, finding the right questions to ask - rather than looking for answers, looking for better questions.  Many of her students were very instructive and very inventive. 
\par 
\par She used to feel that she was being sidelined because of her focus on working in her own society, her own country and working in cities.  However, when she was invited to be the C
hair of the Association of Social Anthropologists, the reason for the invitation was directly related to her work focus. 
\par 
\par She enjoys writing short stories, restoring old houses, walking and reading, though she feels as though she is constantly doing fieldwork, trying to understand people\rquote s behaviour.   
